2026-04-21 01:26:40 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['power supply internal wiring / LED branch', 'control module cable pair between PSU and control module'] hypothesis_explanation='The measurements show that the PSU output labeled “+” is actually at −12 V with respect to ground and the “−” lead is at 0 V. The control-module red LED is on, which in this design only occurs when the 12 V and 0 V lines from the power supply are swapped at the control-module input. Therefore, there are two configuration faults:\n1) Inside or at the output of the power-supply module, the positive and negative lines are wired so that the cable designated as + is actually driven negative with respect to the PSU LED reference, keeping the green LED reverse‑biased and off.\n2) At the connection between the power-supply module and the control module, the two output cables are plugged in with reversed polarity, so the control-module red “switched cables indicator” LED is forward biased and lit, and the load module receives reversed polarity. The diode in series with the load therefore blocks current and the lamp never turns on.\nCorrecting these polarity/configuration errors (ensuring the PSU + lead is truly the positive output and that this lead connects to the control module + input, with the 0 V lead to the corresponding 0 V input) should restore proper operation of the lamp and the green PSU LED, and turn off the red inverted-cables indicator.'
