DESCRIPTION: With the present wiring (PSU ‘+’ → control ‘+ in’, PSU ‘−’ → control ‘− in’, control ‘+ out’ → load ‘+’, control ‘− out’ → load ‘−’) and PSU still providing −12 V on its ‘+’ terminal relative to ‘−’, measure the DC voltage at: (1) the load‑module ‘+’ input terminal, (2) the node immediately after the series diode feeding the lamps, and (3) both sides of the main lamp and the internal indicator lamp, all relative to the PSU ‘−’ (0 V) reference. Report the node voltages and whether either lamp shows any faint glow. This will determine whether the load module wiring or diode orientation prevents current, or if the problem remains confined upstream.,
RESULT: Measured node voltages (all relative to PSU ‘−’ = 0 V): load-module ‘+’ input is at −11.9872 V; diode anode is at −11.9872 V and cathode at −0.0021 V; both terminals of the main lamp are at −0.0021 V; both terminals of the internal indicator lamp are at −0.0021 V. The internal indicator lamp is not lit and shows no observable internal fault.
Current persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:
No circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.


2026-04-21 01:27:15 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control module inverted‑cables LED branch wiring / LED orientation'] hypothesis_explanation='All module‑to‑module cabling is confirmed correct: PSU ‘+’→control ‘+in’, PSU ‘−’→control ‘−in’, control ‘+out’→load ‘+’, control ‘−out’→load ‘−’. The PSU itself is also wired correctly internally (its ‘+’ node is simply at −12 V with respect to the chosen 0 V reference), and the load module behaves as expected given the network nodes: its series diode and lamps sit at about −0.0021 V, i.e., at the same potential on both lamp terminals, so no lamp current flows.\n\nThe red inverted‑cables LED branch shows abnormal node potentials: resistor ‘p’ side at −11.99 V, resistor ‘n’ side and LED cathode at −1.29 V, LED anode at ≈0 V. Thus the LED has about +1.29 V from anode to cathode (forward‑biased) and is lit, even though the external cabling is not inverted. More importantly, the branch biases an intermediate node to −1.29 V instead of 0 V, and this same node appears at the cathode of the load‑module series diode. As a result, the diode from −11.99 V to −1.29 V sees forward bias and clamps that node around −1.29 V, leaving the lamp node at ≈0 V but with no potential across the lamp filaments; hence the lamp never lights regardless of switch operation.\n\nThis behavior can only occur if the inverted‑cables indicator branch inside the control module is miswired or the LED is installed with incorrect orientation relative to its schematic, so that it sources current and creates the −1.29 V intermediate node even when the cables are connected correctly. That miswired branch both turns the red LED on falsely and distorts the node voltages so the downstream diode/lamp branch cannot see the correct supply. Therefore the root cause is an internal wiring / orientation fault in the control module’s inverted‑cables LED branch, not in the external cabling or other modules.'
