2026-04-21 01:27:52 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control‑module cable pair between control and load modules (mis‑mated plug pair)'] hypothesis_explanation='All components and internal wirings so far tested behave consistently with a healthy circuit under a globally reversed PSU polarity (PSU ‘+’ at −12 V, ‘−’ at 0 V). In that situation the red inverted‑cables LED is correctly forward‑biased and lit, and the load‑module input sees −12 V at its ‘+’ terminal, with the series diode then clamping the lamp node near 0 V, so neither lamp can light—this is exactly what we measure. That means the *only* real fault is that the intended polarity between modules is reversed somewhere in the cabling. \n\nEarlier visual checks only confirmed that each plug’s two conductors are kept as a pair (marked ‘+’ with ‘+’, ‘−’ with ‘−’) but cannot detect if one of those plug pairs itself has been plugged into the wrong mating connector orientation (i.e., the physical pair between the control and load cube is rotated so that the line that should be 0 V is actually carrying the −12 V from the PSU and vice versa). With identical, unmarked two‑wire connectors, this mis‑mating is entirely plausible and would not be revealed by the prior “no cross‑connection” observation.\n\nThus the most probable root cause is a connection/configuration fault: the two‑wire plug pair between the control module and the load module is mis‑mated (rotated), resulting in global polarity inversion down the chain while every internal module wiring remains correct. Correcting that plug orientation so that the actual 12 V line from the PSU reaches the diode/lamp branch with the proper polarity will extinguish the red LED and allow the main lamp to operate when the switch is closed.'
